snippet.textDisplay:
The most irritating part about the whole thing is this time next year the coronavirus will be old news. Just like SARS, Swine Flu, Avian Influenza, MERS and every other "outbreak" the media has used to cause fear and panic in the ill-informed. Here is some information I have yet to see a news organization cover. According to the CDC's website, serious illnesses only occur in about 16% of the population. It's the elderly and people with pre-existing medical conditions that need to be most concerned. So far there are about 65,000 CLOSED cases for the covid-19 virus and in those cases, roughly 61,000 of the 65,000 cases recovered or 94% survived. That leaves about 42,000 active cases, as of today, of the virus and about 6,000 of those cases are considered serious. With no information on the patients currently infected, it's hard to determine how many of those will survive. To put things in perspective the common flu killed 34,200 in the 2018-2019 flu season, and anywhere from 20,000-52,000 this flu season. So wash your hands, keep your hands out of your mouth, cover your mouth when you cough, and just stay home if you're sick. Like you should when you have the flu or any other respiratory virus. If anyone wants to look up any of this for themselves I have provided the links to the websites at the bottom.


https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/summary.html
https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/
https://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/burden/2018-2019.html
https://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/burden/preliminary-in-season-estimates.htm

For severe and highly infectious cases, a mobile capsule negative pressure chamber tube bed can be provided, similar to the experimental diagnosis and treatment bed type of a childcare box, allowing individual treatment of severely diagnosed patients. The device is used for static sterilization, irradiation and sterilization of high temperature and ultraviolet catalysts, and the central government will study emergency treatment.  In the future, the government is advised to study the vaccine as soon as possible, and to conduct the research before the first transmission of infectious diseases in the community.
